----

Australia has traditionally been skeptical of patents.  The patent system and in particular its expansion into software and business methods were pushed on Australia by uncontrolled judicial developments and trade treaties with the US.  The subject flared up again in 2004 thanks to the AU-US Free Trade Agreement and some new decisions on business methods.

== News and Chronology ==

Feel free to add news (e.g. [http://news.google.com/search?hl=en&q=Australia+software+patent&btnG=Search+News from Google]) to the top.

 * 2004-11-04 [:FfiiAuEn: AU] [http://www.theage.com.au/news/Breaking/Patents-pose-equal-threat-to-all-software/2004/11/04/1099362275074.html The Age: Patents 'pose equal threat to all software']
 * 2004-11-04 [:FfiiAuEn: AU] [http://www.zdnet.com.au/news/business/0,39023166,39165409,00.htm ZDNet.com.au: Patent fear plagues Aussie developers]
 * 2004-10-14 [http://www.bakercyberlawcentre.org/2004/talks/LTT_04_stallman.htm RMS talk in Sydney] (--> [:RmsToursEn: RMS Tours])
 * 2004-09-07 [:Ausfta040907En: MP Pierce: AUSFTA only harmonises the status quo on software patents]
 * 2004-08-06 [:Ausfta040806En: Software groups concerned about "harmonisation of patent law" with US, gov't sees no danger]
 * 2004-08-03 [http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20040803/1122232.shtml TechDirt: US Exports DMCA & Software Patents To Australia]
 * 2004-08-03 [http://www.brainbox.com.au/brainbox/home.nsf/0/C927B8A15DD6093849256EE40036DC26?opendocument Brainbox: How AUSFTA could damage local software industry] -- discussion of SMH/Gittins article
 * 2004-08-02 [http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/08/01/1091298576840.html?oneclick=true SMH/Gittins: AU-US Trade Agreement a free kick for US software patent racketeers] 
 * 2004-07-19 [:Ausfta040719En: senior diplomat warns about US imposition of patents as non-tarifary trade barriers through proposed "Free Trade Agreement"]
 * 2004-06-23 DFAT minister Vaile [http://www.trademinister.gov.au/speeches/2004/040623_2nd_reading_usfta.html introduces AUSFTA Implementation Bill]
 * 2004-05-31 [http://www.aph.gov.au/Library/pubs/rp/2003-04/04rp14.htm David Richardson study on IPR & AUSFTA] -- research paper about the US strategy in the AUSFTA.  The term "IPR" is largely used as a synonym for "patents"
 * 2004-05-18 [http://www.dfat.gov.au/ DFAT] minister Vaile [http://www.dfat.gov.au/trade/negotiations/us.html signs] the [http://www.dfat.gov.au/trade/negotiations/us_fta/final-text/index.html AUSFTA] in Washington (on the same day in Brussels, the EU Council [:Cons040518En: reaches political agreement for removal of all limits on patentability])
 * 2004-03-04 AUSFTA [http://www.dfat.gov.au/trade/negotiations/us_fta/final-text/index.html Full Text] released, [http://www.dfat.gov.au/trade/negotiations/us_fta/final-text/chapter_17.html chapter 17 on "intellectual property rights"]
 * 2004-02-08 Trade Minister Mark Vaile announces that Australia and the US have agreed to AUSFTA
 * 1986 Mandeville Study Report, commissioned by AU government, warns that the patent system has been unuseful as a tool for fostering innovation in general and should not be allowed to trespass into fields such as software and genetics in particular.  Two years later, the AU PTO publishes new guidelines to allow patents on "software-related inventions"

== Outline ==

The debate about the AU-US Free Trade Agreement is documented [http://kwiki.ffii.org/Ausfta04En separately].

